    "sourceText": "Assignment 1 Experiment 1: Propagation Model Comparison using Mininet-WiFi Aim To study the effect of different wireless propagation models on signal strength, latency, packet delivery, and throughput in a wireless network using Mininet-WiFi. 1. Introduction Wireless propagation models determine how radio signals attenuate as they travel through space. Different models represent different environmental conditions and directly affect network performance metrics such as received signal strength, delay, packet loss, and throughput. The following propagation models were analyzed: 1. Free Space Model The Free Space model assumes a clear line-of-sight (LOS) path between transmitter and receiver without any obstacles or reflections. It provides the strongest signal and is often used as a theoretical baseline. 2. Two-Ray Ground Model The Two-Ray Ground model considers both the direct signal path and a reflected path from the ground. It is more suitable for outdoor environments and predicts more realistic signal behavior than the Free Space model. 3. Log-Distance Model The Log-Distance model introduces path loss based on distance and environmental factors. It is commonly used to represent indoor, urban, and obstructed wireless environments where signals experience attenuation due to walls, buildings, and other obstacles. 2. Wireless Network Topology A wireless network topology was created using Mininet-WiFi consisting of: Device Count Access Points 1 Stations 3 The stations were placed at different distances from the Access Point to observe the effect of propagation models on signal strength and network performance. Station Distance from AP sta1 40 m sta2 5 m sta3 30 m 3. Performance Metrics The following parameters were measured: \u25cf Received Signal Strength (RSSI) \u25cf Round Trip Time (RTT) \u25cf Packet Loss \u25cf Throughput \u25cf Signal variation under mobility 4. Free Space Propagation Model Signal strength and RTT were measured using ping and wireless interface statistics. Results Station Distance (m) Signal Strength (dBm) RTT (ms) Packet Loss sta1 40 -52.1 3.86 0% sta2 5 -34.1 1.85 0% sta3 30 -49.6 3.80 0% Link Throughput: 8.17 Mbps Mobility Signal Range: -52.1 dBm to -20.1 dBm Inference The Free Space model produced the strongest received signal levels and the highest throughput. Since it assumes a perfect line-of-sight environment without reflections or obstructions, it represents the ideal wireless communication scenario. 5. Two-Ray Ground Propagation Model The same measurements were repeated using the Two-Ray Ground propagation model. Results Station Distance (m) Signal Strength (dBm) RTT (ms) Packet Loss sta1 40 -52.1 5.65 0% sta2 5 -34.1 3.20 0% sta3 30 -49.6 5.12 0% Link Throughput: 6.21 Mbps Mobility Signal Range: -52.1 dBm to -20.1 dBm Inference The Two-Ray Ground model showed increased RTT and reduced throughput compared to the Free Space model. Ground reflections introduce additional signal propagation effects, making the model more realistic for outdoor wireless deployments. 6. Log-Distance Propagation Model Measurements were then performed using the Log-Distance propagation model. Results Station Distance (m) Signal Strength (dBm) RTT (ms) Packet Loss sta1 40 -65.7 6.61 0% sta2 5 -39.3 3.25 0% sta3 30 -65.2 6.71 0% Link Throughput: 4.68 Mbps Mobility Signal Range: -65.4 dBm to -19.0 dBm Inference The Log-Distance model produced the lowest signal strengths and throughput values. The higher path loss introduced by this model simulates realistic indoor and urban environments where obstacles, shadowing, and multipath fading significantly attenuate wireless signals. 7. Comparison of Propagation Models Signal Strength Comparison Model Signal Strength Range (dBm) Free Space -52.1 to -20.1 Two-Ray Ground -52.1 to -20.1 Log-Distance -65.4 to -19.0 Throughput Comparison Model Throughput (Mbps) Free Space 8.17 Two-Ray Ground 6.21 Log-Distance 4.68 RTT Comparison Model Average RTT (ms) Free Space 3.17 Two-Ray Ground 4.66 Log-Distance 5.52 8. Graphs Generated The following graphs were plotted for analysis: Graph 1: Signal Strength / Interference Levels Shows variation in received signal strength under different propagation models. Graph 2: Mobility Model Behavior Illustrates signal fluctuations as stations move within the wireless coverage area. Graph 3: Throughput and RTT Analysis Compares throughput and delay performance across propagation models. Graph 4: Overall Model Comparison Provides a combined comparison of signal strength, throughput, RTT, and packet loss. 9. Key Observations Propagation Model Observation Free Space Best signal strength and highest throughput due to ideal LOS assumptions. Two-Ray Ground Moderate performance; incorporates ground reflection effects and is suitable for outdoor environments. Log-Distance Lowest signal strength and throughput; represents realistic indoor and urban propagation conditions. 10. Conclusion This experiment demonstrated the significant impact of propagation models on wireless network performance. The Free Space model achieved the highest throughput and strongest signal levels, while the Log-Distance model exhibited greater signal attenuation and reduced throughput due to increased path loss. The Two-Ray Ground model provided intermediate performance and better represented outdoor environments. Therefore, selecting an appropriate propagation model is essential for realistic wireless network simulation and performance evaluation in Mininet-WiFi.",
