    "sourceText": "Assignment 2 Assignment 2 Wireless Network Simulation using Mininet-WiFi Aim: To study wireless network behavior using the Mininet-WiFi emulator by performing the following tasks: To understand the effect of the fading constant (path loss exponent) on signal attenuation in wireless communication. To design and simulate a wireless network topology consisting of m access points and n stations distributed across a geographic area . To analyze wireless network performance by plotting graphs for: \u25cb Distance vs Received Signal Strength \u25cb Distance vs Throughput \u25cb Bitrate vs Throughput 1. Effect of Fading Constant in Wireless Communication In wireless communication models, the \"fading constant\" (also known as the Path Loss Exponent, usually denoted by gamma de\ufb01nes the rate at which the transmitted signal power decays as the distance between the transmitter and receiver increases. \u25cf Theoretical Free Space: In a perfect vacuum with a clear line-of-sight, the fading constant is exactly 2 , meaning signal power decreases with the square of the distance (Inverse Square Law). \u25cf Real-World Environments: In practical scenarios (like campuses, of\ufb01ces, or urban areas), signals experience re\ufb02ection, diffraction, and scattering due to obstacles like walls and trees. This causes the fading constant to increase to 3, 4, or even 6 . \u25cf Overall Effect: A higher fading constant drastically accelerates signal attenuation. This effectively reduces the maximum transmission range of the Access Point, increases packet loss at the edge of the network, and lowers the overall achievable throughput for mobile stations. 2. Wireless Network Topology A wireless network was created using Mininet-WiFi MiniEdit consisting of: Access points 3 Stations 4 The stations were placed across the geographic area so that different distances from the access points could be observed. Each station associates with the nearest access point within its wireless range. Fig : Mobility Model : RandomWalk 3. Mobility Models To simulate node movement, mobility models were applied. Mininet-WiFi supports several mobility models including: \u25cf RandomWalk \u25cf RandomWaypoint \u25cf RandomDirection \u25cf GaussMarkov \u25cf TruncatedLevyWalk In this experiment, the RandomWalk mobility model was used. Example con\ufb01guration: net.setMobilityModel(time=0, model='RandomWalk', max_x=1000, max_y=1000, seed=20) Other mobility models can be implemented in the same way by changing the model parameter. 4. Distance vs Received Signal Strength {distance,Signal strength} was obtained from the station interface using: py (((sta1.position[0]-ap1.position[0])**2+(sta1.position[1]-ap1.position[1])**2)**0.5, sta1.cmd('iw dev sta1-wlan0 link | grep signal')) Distance (m) Signal Strength (dBm) 129 -79 140 -80 143 -80 147 -81 149 -81 159 -82 176 -83 202 -85 Inference : This con\ufb01rms that signal attenuation increases with distance, which is consistent with wireless propagation models. 5. Distance vs Throughput Throughput was measured using iperf. Start server: sta2 iperf -s & Run throughput test: sta1 iperf -c 10.0.0.2 -t 2 Distance (m) Throughput (Mbps) 102 3.45 120 2.61 130 1.75 139 3.55 146 3.51 162 4.20 189 3.77 219 3.47 239 3.36 Inference: Throughput generally decreases or \ufb02uctuates as distance increases due to reduced signal strength and node mobility. 6. Modifying Bitrate Link bitrate was modi\ufb01ed in the topology \ufb01le: net.addLink(sta1, ap1, bw=10) net.addLink(sta2, ap1, bw=20) net.addLink(sta3, ap2, bw=54) net.addLink(sta4, ap3, bw=11) Throughput was measured again using iperf . Statio n Bitrate (Mbps) Throughput (Mbps) sta1 10 4.17 sta2 20 4.63 sta3 54 4.02 sta4 11 5.01 Inference: Increasing bitrate raises the potential data rate, but actual throughput depends on signal quality, interference, and network overhead.",
