    "number": 3,
    "sourceText": "Assignment 3 Experiment 3: Active vs Passive Scanning using Mininet-WiFi Aim To compare Active Scanning and Passive Scanning techniques in wireless networks by analyzing discovery time, power consumption, and network response using Mininet-WiFi. 1. Introduction Wireless stations must discover available Access Points (APs) before establishing a connection. This process is known as wireless scanning. Two scanning techniques are commonly used: 1. Active Scanning In Active Scanning, a station actively broadcasts Probe Request frames and waits for Probe Response frames from nearby Access Points. This method allows devices to discover networks quickly. 2. Passive Scanning In Passive Scanning, a station listens for periodic Beacon Frames transmitted by Access Points. Since the station waits for beacons instead of transmitting requests, the discovery process is generally slower. 2. Wireless Network Topology A wireless network was created using Mininet-WiFi consisting of: Device Count Access Point 1 Station 1 The station was configured to perform both Active and Passive scanning while measuring discovery time, received bytes, and network latency. 3. Performance Parameters The following metrics were analyzed: \u25cf Discovery Time \u25cf Power Consumption (RX Bytes) \u25cf Round Trip Time (RTT) 4. Discovery Time Analysis The time required for the station to discover and associate with the Access Point was measured. Results Scanning Method Discovery Time (s) Active Scanning 0.010 Passive Scanning 0.012 Difference: 0.002 s Faster Method: Active Scanning Inference Active Scanning discovers nearby Access Points faster because the station actively sends Probe Request frames and receives immediate responses. Passive Scanning relies on waiting for beacon transmissions, resulting in slightly longer discovery times. 5. Power Consumption Analysis Power consumption was estimated using the number of received bytes during the scanning process. Results Scanning Method RX Bytes Active Scanning 1707 bytes Passive Scanning 1707 bytes Inference Both scanning methods consumed nearly the same amount of received data in this experiment. However, Active Scanning generally incurs additional transmission overhead due to Probe Request frames, whereas Passive Scanning primarily listens for beacon frames. 6. Network Response Analysis (RTT) Network latency was measured using Round Trip Time (RTT). Results Scanning Method Average RTT (ms) Active Scanning 7.233 Passive Scanning 7.060 Inference The RTT values are very similar for both scanning methods because once association is completed, communication occurs through the same Access Point and wireless channel. The scanning mechanism mainly affects network discovery rather than data transmission performance. 7. Comparison of Active and Passive Scanning Parameter Active Scanning Passive Scanning Discovery Time 0.010 s 0.012 s RX Bytes 1707 bytes 1707 bytes Average RTT 7.233 ms 7.060 ms Discovery Speed Faster Slower Probe Requests Yes No Beacon Dependence No Yes 8. Graphs Generated The following graphs can be plotted for analysis: Graph 1: Scanning Method vs Discovery Time Compares the time required to discover and connect to an Access Point. Graph 2: Scanning Method vs Power Consumption Shows the amount of data exchanged during scanning. Graph 3: Scanning Method vs RTT Compares network response times after association. 9. Key Observations \u25cf Active Scanning achieved faster network discovery by transmitting Probe Request frames. \u25cf Passive Scanning required waiting for beacon frames from the Access Point, resulting in slightly longer discovery times. \u25cf Both methods showed nearly identical power consumption in terms of received bytes. \u25cf Network latency (RTT) remained almost the same after successful association. \u25cf Active Scanning is preferred when rapid network discovery is required, while Passive Scanning is useful for reducing wireless channel activity. 10. Conclusion This experiment compared Active and Passive Scanning techniques in a wireless network using Mininet-WiFi. Active Scanning provided faster Access Point discovery due to the use of Probe Request messages, whereas Passive Scanning relied on beacon reception and required slightly more time. The RTT and received bytes were nearly identical for both methods, indicating that scanning primarily affects the association phase rather than subsequent communication performance. Therefore, Active Scanning is generally preferred for faster connectivity, while Passive Scanning may be used in environments where minimizing channel transmissions is desirable.",
