    "number": 4,
    "sourceText": "Assignment 4 Experiment 4: Mobile Node Handover Between Two Access Points using Mininet-WiFi Aim To study the handover process of a mobile wireless station moving between two Access Points and analyze the effects on signal strength, latency, and packet loss using Mininet-WiFi. 1. Introduction In wireless networks, a handover (handoff) occurs when a mobile station moves out of the coverage area of one Access Point (AP) and connects to another AP with a stronger signal. Handover is essential for maintaining uninterrupted connectivity in mobile environments such as: \u25cf Campus Wi-Fi networks \u25cf Cellular networks \u25cf Smart transportation systems \u25cf Mobile IoT deployments The quality of handover directly affects network performance in terms of signal strength, delay, and packet loss. 2. Wireless Network Topology A wireless topology was created in Mininet-WiFi consisting of: Device Count Access Points 2 Mobile Station 1 Access Point Configuration Access Point Position (x-coordinate) Channel AP1 x = 20 Channel 1 AP2 x = 80 Channel 6 Mobile Node Movement The mobile station moved continuously from: x = 10 \u2192 x = 90 allowing it to travel through the coverage regions of both Access Points and trigger a handover event. 3. Mobility Model The mobile node was configured to move across the network area, enabling observation of signal variation and AP association changes. As the station moved: \u25cf Distance from AP1 increased. \u25cf Distance from AP2 decreased. \u25cf Signal strength from AP1 gradually weakened. \u25cf Signal strength from AP2 gradually improved. \u25cf The station automatically associated with the Access Point offering the stronger signal. 4. Handover Analysis During mobility, the station switched its association from AP1 to AP2. Handover Event Details Parameter Value Handover Position x = 70 Time Elapsed 56.9 s Previous AP 02:00:00:00:02:00 New AP 02:00:00:00:03:00 Signal Strength at Handover -59.0 dBm RTT at Handover 3.04 ms Packet Loss at Handover 0 % 5. Signal Strength Behavior During Mobility As the station moved away from AP1, the received signal strength gradually decreased. Simultaneously, the signal received from AP2 increased as the station approached its coverage area. Observation Movement Phase Signal Behavior Near AP1 Strong AP1 signal Moving Away from AP1 Signal gradually decreases Handover Region Signals from both APs become comparable Near AP2 Strong AP2 signal Inference The handover occurred when AP2 provided a stronger signal than AP1. This ensured continuous connectivity while the station moved across the network. 6. RTT Analysis During Handover Network latency was monitored throughout the movement. Result Parameter Value RTT at Handover 3.04 ms Inference A slight increase in RTT was observed near the handover region due to reassociation procedures. However, the latency remained within acceptable limits, indicating a smooth transition between Access Points. 7. Packet Loss Analysis Packet transmission was continuously monitored during mobility. Result Parameter Value Packet Loss at Handover 0 % Inference No packet loss was observed during the handover process. This indicates that the network successfully maintained communication while switching between Access Points. 8. Handover Performance Summary Parameter Observation Handover Position x = 70 Handover Time 56.9 s Signal at Handover -59.0 dBm RTT at Handover 3.04 ms Packet Loss 0 % Connectivity Status Successfully maintained 9. Graphs Generated The following graphs were generated for performance analysis: Graph 1: Position vs Signal Strength Shows the decrease in AP1 signal and increase in AP2 signal as the station moves. Graph 2: Position vs RTT Illustrates latency variations during mobility and handover. Graph 3: Position vs Packet Loss Displays packet loss behavior throughout the movement. Graph 4: Handover Performance Analysis Combined visualization of signal strength, RTT, and packet loss during the handover process. 10. Key Observations \u25cf Signal strength from AP1 decreased continuously as the mobile node moved away from it. \u25cf Signal strength from AP2 increased as the node approached its coverage region. \u25cf The handover occurred at position x = 70 when AP2 became the stronger Access Point. \u25cf RTT showed a slight increase near the handover zone due to reassociation procedures. \u25cf No packet loss occurred during the transition. \u25cf Connectivity was successfully maintained after association with AP2. 11. Conclusion This experiment demonstrated the handover mechanism in a wireless network using Mininet-WiFi. As the mobile station moved from AP1 toward AP2, the received signal from AP1 weakened while the signal from AP2 strengthened. A successful handover occurred at x = 70 after 56.9 seconds , with a signal strength of \u221259.0 dBm . The network maintained uninterrupted communication with 0% packet loss and minimal latency increase, demonstrating the effectiveness of wireless mobility management and seamless Access Point reassociation in maintaining continuous network connectivity.",
