    "number": 5,
    "sourceText": "Assignment 5 Experiment 5: Open5GS Core Setup and Subscriber Configuration Aim To deploy and configure the Open5GS 5G Core Network on Ubuntu, establish subscriber management using MongoDB, and validate core network functionality through the Open5GS WebUI. 1. Introduction Open5GS is an open-source implementation of the 5G Standalone (SA) Core Network that supports key 5G network functions such as: \u25cf Access and Mobility Management Function (AMF) \u25cf Session Management Function (SMF) \u25cf User Plane Function (UPF) \u25cf Unified Data Management (UDM) \u25cf Authentication Server Function (AUSF) \u25cf Policy Control Function (PCF) In this experiment, Open5GS was deployed on Ubuntu and integrated with MongoDB for subscriber management. The Open5GS WebUI was used to configure subscribers and validate core network operation. This setup forms the foundation for advanced 5G experiments involving UERANSIM, Network Slicing, Mobile Edge Computing (MEC), and Smart Healthcare applications. 2. Environment Setup The following software components were used: Component Description Operating System Ubuntu Open5GS 5G Core Network UERANSIM 5G UE and gNB Simulator MongoDB Subscriber Database Node.js / NPM Open5GS WebUI Support Installation Locations Software Installation Path Open5GS ~/open5gs UERANSIM ~/UERANSIM WebUI ~/open5gs/webui 3. Objective The objectives of this experiment were: \u25cf Deploy Open5GS 5G Core Network. \u25cf Configure MongoDB as the subscriber database. \u25cf Start and verify Open5GS core services. \u25cf Launch Open5GS WebUI. \u25cf Add and configure a subscriber profile. \u25cf Validate successful core network operation. 4. Procedure Step 1: Install Open5GS and MongoDB Open5GS and MongoDB were installed on Ubuntu. MongoDB was configured as the backend database for storing subscriber information. Step 2: Start Open5GS Core Services The Open5GS network functions were started using: sudo systemctl start open5gs-* Service status was verified using: systemctl status open5gs-* Step 3: Launch Open5GS WebUI Navigate to the WebUI directory: cd ~/open5gs/webui Install required packages: npm install Start the WebUI: npm run dev Step 4: Access WebUI Open a web browser and access: http://localhost:9999 The Open5GS management dashboard was successfully displayed. Step 5: Add Subscriber A new subscriber was created using the WebUI with the following configuration: Parameter Value IMSI 99970000000000 1 APN Internet The subscriber profile was saved successfully in the MongoDB database. 5. Subscriber Configuration Configured Subscriber Details Parameter Value IMSI 99970000000000 1 APN internet Status Active Database MongoDB Inference The subscriber information was successfully stored and became available for future UE registration and authentication procedures. 6. Validation of Open5GS Core The following checks were performed: Verification Item Status Open5GS Services Running Successfu l MongoDB Connected Successfu l WebUI Accessible Successfu l Subscriber Added Successfu l Core Network Operational Successfu l 7. Results Core Network Status Component Result Open5GS Core Operational MongoDB Database Operational Open5GS WebUI Operational Subscriber Database Configured Successfully Subscriber Information IMSI APN 99970000000000 1 internet 8. Figures Figure 1: Open5GS WebUI Access The Open5GS WebUI dashboard was successfully accessed through: http://localhost:9999 This interface provides management of subscribers, sessions, and core network configurations. Figure 2: Subscriber Configuration The subscriber profile with IMSI 999700000000001 and APN internet was successfully created and stored in the MongoDB database. 9. Key Observations \u25cf Open5GS was successfully installed and configured on Ubuntu. \u25cf MongoDB functioned correctly as the subscriber database backend. \u25cf All Open5GS core network functions started without errors. \u25cf The WebUI provided an easy interface for subscriber management. \u25cf Subscriber IMSI 999700000000001 was successfully added. \u25cf The configured APN internet was stored correctly. \u25cf The system was ready for UE registration and further 5G experiments using UERANSIM. 10. Conclusion This experiment successfully deployed and validated the Open5GS 5G Standalone Core Network on Ubuntu. MongoDB was configured as the subscriber database, and the Open5GS WebUI was used to manage subscriber information. A subscriber with IMSI 999700000000001 and APN internet was successfully added, confirming proper operation of the core network infrastructure. The setup provides a functional foundation for subsequent experiments involving UERANSIM integration, UE registration, network slicing, Mobile Edge Computing (MEC), and end-to-end 5G application deployment.",
