    "number": 7,
    "sourceText": "Assignment 7 Experiment 7: UE Registration and PDU Session Establishment Aim To configure and register a User Equipment (UE) with the Open5GS 5G Core Network using UERANSIM and establish a PDU (Packet Data Unit) Session for data communication. 1. Introduction In a 5G Standalone (SA) network, the User Equipment (UE) must first register with the 5G Core before accessing network services. During registration, the UE is authenticated using subscriber credentials stored in the Open5GS database. After successful registration, a PDU Session is established, allowing the UE to obtain an IP address and exchange data through the network. This experiment demonstrates UE registration, authentication, and PDU Session establishment using UERANSIM and Open5GS. 2. Objective The objectives of this experiment were: \u25cf Configure a simulated UE in UERANSIM. \u25cf Register the UE with the Open5GS Core. \u25cf Authenticate the subscriber using stored credentials. \u25cf Establish a PDU Session. \u25cf Obtain an IP address for data communication. \u25cf Verify successful UE connectivity. 3. Prerequisites Before performing UE registration, the following components were operational: Component Status Open5GS Core Network Running MongoDB Database Running Subscriber Configuration Completed gNB Integration Successful NG Setup Successful UERANSIM Installation Completed 4. UE Configuration The UE configuration file was located at: ~/UERANSIM/config/open5gs-ue.yaml The subscriber information configured in Open5GS was used in the UE configuration. Subscriber Parameters Parameter Value IMSI 99970000000000 1 Authentication Key Configured OPC Configured APN internet These values must exactly match the subscriber profile stored in Open5GS. 5. Procedure Step 1: Verify Subscriber Information Ensure the subscriber exists in the Open5GS WebUI and verify: \u25cf IMSI \u25cf Authentication Key \u25cf OPC \u25cf APN Step 2: Configure UE Open the UE configuration file: nano ~/UERANSIM/config/open5gs-ue.yaml Update: \u25cf IMSI \u25cf Key \u25cf OPC \u25cf APN to match the subscriber database. Step 3: Start the UE Launch the UE simulator: sudo ./build/nr-ue -c config/open5gs-ue.yaml The UE begins the registration procedure with the 5G Core. Step 4: Resolve SQN Mismatch (If Required) If authentication fails due to sequence number mismatch, perform resynchronization between the UE and Open5GS subscriber database. This allows successful authentication and registration. Step 5: Enable Internet Connectivity (Optional) Enable packet forwarding: sysctl -w net.ipv4.ip_forward=1 Configure NAT: iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING -o eth0 -j MASQUERADE These commands allow external network access through the host machine. 6. UE Registration Procedure The following sequence occurred during registration: 1. UE sends Registration Request. 2. AMF receives registration information. 3. AUSF performs authentication. 4. UDM verifies subscriber credentials. 5. Registration Accept message is sent. 6. UE enters Registered state. Registration Flow UE ------ Registration Request ------> AMF UE <----- Authentication Challenge --- AMF UE ------ Authentication Response ---> AMF UE <----- Registration Accept -------- AMF 7. PDU Session Establishment After registration, the UE requested a PDU Session. The following actions occurred: 1. UE requests PDU Session. 2. SMF processes the request. 3. UPF allocates user-plane resources. 4. IP address is assigned. 5. Session becomes active. Assigned IP Address Parameter Value UE IP Address 10.45.0. 2 PDU Session Flow UE ------ PDU Session Request ------> SMF UE <----- PDU Session Accept ------- SMF UE <----- IP Allocation ------------ UPF 8. Results UE Registration Status Parameter Result UE Started Successfully Yes Authentication Successful Yes Registration Request Sent Yes Registration Accept Received Yes UE Registered Yes PDU Session Status Parameter Result PDU Session Request Successfu l PDU Session Accepted Successfu l IP Address Assigned 10.45.0.2 Data Session Active Yes 9. Verification Registration Verification The UE console displayed: \u25cf Registration Request \u25cf Authentication Success \u25cf Registration Accept indicating successful attachment to the 5G Core Network. PDU Session Verification The console output confirmed: \u25cf PDU Session Establishment \u25cf IP Address Allocation \u25cf Active Data Connectivity Inference The successful registration process verified that the UE credentials matched the subscriber information configured in Open5GS. The establishment of the PDU Session confirmed successful user-plane connectivity through the 5G Core. 10. Figures Figure 4: UE Registration Accept The UE terminal displayed a Registration Accept message, confirming successful authentication and registration with the Open5GS Core Network. Figure 5: PDU Session Established The UE successfully established a PDU Session and received the IP address 10.45.0.2 , enabling data communication through the 5G network. 11. Key Observations \u25cf UE configuration successfully matched the subscriber profile. \u25cf Authentication was completed successfully using IMSI, Key, and OPC. \u25cf Registration Accept message was received from the AMF. \u25cf The UE entered the Registered state. \u25cf A PDU Session was successfully established. \u25cf The UE was assigned the IP address 10.45.0.2 . \u25cf NAT and IP forwarding enabled external connectivity when required. \u25cf End-to-end communication between UE and the 5G Core was successfully established. 12. Conclusion This experiment successfully demonstrated UE registration and PDU Session establishment in a 5G Standalone network using Open5GS and UERANSIM. The UE authenticated using subscriber credentials stored in Open5GS and successfully received a Registration Accept message. A PDU Session was subsequently established, and the UE was assigned the IP address 10.45.0.2 , confirming successful user-plane connectivity. This experiment validates the complete attachment procedure and forms the basis for advanced 5G services such as network slicing, MEC deployment, and application-specific use cases",
