    "sourceText": "Assignment 8 Experiment 8: Network Slicing in Open5GS Aim To implement and validate multiple network slices in a 5G Standalone (SA) network using Open5GS and UERANSIM by configuring multiple S-NSSAIs and verifying slice-based UE registration. 1. Introduction Network Slicing is one of the key features of 5G networks that enables a single physical network infrastructure to be partitioned into multiple logical networks, called network slices . Each slice can be optimized for different services and performance requirements. Examples of 5G network slices include: \u25cf eMBB (Enhanced Mobile Broadband) \u2013 High data rate applications. \u25cf URLLC (Ultra-Reliable Low Latency Communication) \u2013 Mission-critical services. \u25cf mMTC (Massive Machine Type Communication) \u2013 IoT and sensor networks. In 5G, slices are identified using the Single Network Slice Selection Assistance Information (S-NSSAI) , which contains: \u25cf SST (Slice/Service Type) \u25cf SD (Slice Differentiator) (optional) This experiment demonstrates the configuration of multiple network slices in Open5GS and verifies UE registration across different slices. 2. Objective The objectives of this experiment were: \u25cf Configure multiple network slices in Open5GS. \u25cf Add multiple S-NSSAIs to the AMF configuration. \u25cf Update subscriber slice information. \u25cf Configure UE slice selection. \u25cf Validate registration using different slices. 3. Prerequisites Before implementing network slicing, the following components were operational: Component Status Open5GS Core Network Running MongoDB Database Running Open5GS WebUI Accessibl e gNB Integration Successfu l UE Registration Successfu l PDU Session Establishment Successfu l 4. Network Slice Configuration Slice Definitions Two network slices were configured: Slice SST Slice 1 1 Slice 2 2 These slices represent separate logical networks within the same 5G infrastructure. 5. Procedure Step 1: Modify AMF Configuration Open the AMF configuration file: sudo nano /etc/open5gs/amf.yaml Add multiple S-NSSAI entries under the AMF configuration. Example: plmn_support: - plmn_id: mcc: 999 mnc: 70 s_nssai: - sst: 1 - sst: 2 This enables the AMF to support multiple network slices. Step 2: Restart AMF Service Apply the configuration changes: sudo systemctl restart open5gs-amfd Verify service status: sudo systemctl status open5gs-amfd Step 3: Configure Subscriber Slices Open the Open5GS WebUI and edit the subscriber profile. Add the supported slices: Slice SST Slice 1 1 Slice 2 2 Save the updated subscriber configuration. Step 4: Configure UE Slice Selection Modify the UE configuration file: ~/UERANSIM/config/open5gs-ue.yaml Specify the desired slice. Example for Slice 1: sessions: - type: IPv4 apn: internet slice: sst: 1 Example for Slice 2: sessions: - type: IPv4 apn: internet slice: sst: 2 Step 5: Start UE Launch the UE: sudo ./build/nr-ue -c config/open5gs-ue.yaml Repeat the test using SST 1 and SST 2. 6. Slice-Based Registration During registration, the UE includes its requested S-NSSAI information. The AMF performs: 1. Slice verification. 2. Subscriber authorization. 3. Slice selection. 4. Registration acceptance. Registration Flow UE -------- Registration Request (SST 1/2) --------> AMF UE <------- Registration Accept -------------------- AMF The AMF assigns the UE to the requested network slice if authorized. 7. Results Slice Registration Results Test Case SST Registration Status UE Test 1 1 Successful UE Test 2 2 Successful AMF Slice Support Slice Status SST 1 Enable d SST 2 Enable d Subscriber Slice Access Subscriber Authorized Slices 99970000000000 1 SST 1, SST 2 8. Verification The following observations confirmed successful network slicing: Verification Item Status AMF Configured with Multiple S-NSSAI Successfu l AMF Restarted Successfully Successfu l Subscriber Updated in WebUI Successfu l UE Registered using SST 1 Successfu l UE Registered using SST 2 Successfu l Slice Selection Completed Successfu l Inference The successful registration of the UE on both SST 1 and SST 2 confirmed that the AMF correctly processed multiple network slices and authorized subscriber access according to the configured slice information. 9. Figures Figure 6: AMF Configured with Multiple S-NSSAI The AMF configuration was updated with multiple S-NSSAI entries (SST 1 and SST 2), enabling support for slice-based network access and registration. Figure 7: UE Slice Selection The UE successfully selected and registered with the configured network slice based on the SST specified in the UE configuration file. 10. Key Observations \u25cf Multiple network slices were successfully configured in the AMF. \u25cf S-NSSAI values SST 1 and SST 2 were enabled. \u25cf Subscriber profiles were updated to support multiple slices. \u25cf The UE successfully registered using SST 1. \u25cf The UE successfully registered using SST 2. \u25cf Slice selection was handled correctly by the AMF. \u25cf Open5GS successfully supported slice-based registration. 11. Conclusion This experiment successfully implemented Network Slicing in a 5G Standalone network using Open5GS and UERANSIM. Multiple S-NSSAIs (SST 1 and SST 2) were configured in the AMF and assigned to the subscriber profile. The UE was able to register successfully across both slices, demonstrating slice-based network access and resource separation. This experiment validates one of the core capabilities of 5G architecture and provides a foundation for advanced applications such as service differentiation, MEC deployment, IoT networks, and smart healthcare systems.",
