    "number": 9,
    "sourceText": "Assignment 9 Experiment 9: Mobile Edge Computing (MEC) Latency Analysis Aim To evaluate the performance benefits of Mobile Edge Computing (MEC) by comparing the latency of a local edge server with that of a remote cloud server. 1. Introduction Mobile Edge Computing (MEC) is a key technology in 5G networks that brings computing and storage resources closer to end users. Instead of sending all requests to distant cloud data centers, MEC processes data at the network edge, reducing communication delays and improving application responsiveness. MEC is particularly beneficial for applications requiring: \u25cf Ultra-low latency communication \u25cf Real-time healthcare monitoring \u25cf Autonomous vehicles \u25cf Augmented and Virtual Reality (AR/VR) \u25cf Industrial automation \u25cf Smart city services This experiment compares latency between a local edge server and a remote cloud server to demonstrate the advantages of MEC. 2. Objective The objectives of this experiment were: \u25cf Deploy a local edge server. \u25cf Measure latency between the client and the edge server. \u25cf Measure latency between the client and a remote cloud server. \u25cf Compare the results. \u25cf Demonstrate the latency benefits of MEC. 3. Prerequisites The following components were available before conducting the experiment: Component Status Ubuntu System Running Open5GS Core Operational UERANSIM Operational UE Registration Successful PDU Session Established Network Connectivity Available 4. Mobile Edge Computing Setup Edge Server Deployment A lightweight HTTP server was started on the local machine to emulate an edge computing node. Command used: python3 -m http.server 8080 This server processes requests locally without traversing the internet. 5. Latency Measurement Procedure Step 1: Measure Edge Latency Ping requests were sent to the local edge server: ping 127.0.0.1 -c 5 The loopback address (127.0.0.1) represents an edge service running on the local host. Step 2: Measure Cloud Latency Ping requests were sent to a remote cloud server: ping 8.8.8.8 -c 5 The address 8.8.8.8 represents an external server reachable through the internet. Step 3: Compare Results The average Round Trip Time (RTT) values obtained from both tests were recorded and analyzed. 6. Results Latency Comparison Service Location Average Latency Edge Server (127.0.0.1) 0.03 ms Cloud Server (8.8.8.8) 120 ms 7. Latency Analysis Edge Computing Parameter Value Server Location Local Edge Average RTT 0.03 ms Observation Since computation occurs on the local machine, packets travel a very short distance, resulting in extremely low latency. Cloud Computing Parameter Value Server Location Remote Cloud Average RTT 120 ms Observation The cloud server is located outside the local network. Packets must traverse multiple routers and internet links, resulting in significantly higher latency. 8. Performance Comparison Parameter Edge Computing Cloud Computing Processing Location Network Edge Remote Data Center Average Latency 0.03 ms 120 ms Response Time Very Fast Slower Network Traversal Minimal Extensive Real-Time Suitability Excellent Limited 9. Graphs Generated The following graphs can be plotted for analysis: Graph 1: Service Location vs Latency Compares RTT values for edge and cloud services. Graph 2: Edge vs Cloud Performance Illustrates the reduction in latency achieved using MEC. Graph 3: Response Time Comparison Shows the responsiveness of applications hosted at the edge versus the cloud. 10. Key Observations \u25cf The local edge server achieved an average latency of approximately 0.03 ms . \u25cf The remote cloud server exhibited an average latency of approximately 120 ms . \u25cf Edge latency was significantly lower than cloud latency. \u25cf Data processing at the network edge minimized communication delays. \u25cf Cloud communication required traversal through multiple network hops. \u25cf MEC is highly beneficial for delay-sensitive applications. 11. Applications of MEC The low-latency characteristics of MEC make it suitable for: \u25cf Smart Healthcare Monitoring \u25cf Autonomous Vehicles \u25cf Industrial IoT \u25cf Smart Manufacturing \u25cf Video Analytics \u25cf AR/VR Applications \u25cf Remote Surgery Systems 12. Conclusion This experiment demonstrated the advantages of Mobile Edge Computing by comparing latency between a local edge server and a remote cloud server. The edge server achieved an average latency of 0.03 ms , whereas the cloud server exhibited approximately 120 ms latency. The results clearly show that MEC significantly reduces communication delay by processing data closer to users. Such low-latency performance is essential for real-time 5G applications including smart healthcare, industrial automation, autonomous systems, and other mission-critical services.",
