    "sourceText": "Assignment 10 Experiment 10: End-to-End Smart Healthcare Use Case using 5G Network Slicing and MEC Aim To demonstrate an end-to-end Smart Healthcare application using a 5G Standalone (SA) network by integrating Open5GS, UERANSIM, Network Slicing, and Mobile Edge Computing (MEC) to achieve low-latency communication suitable for healthcare services. 1. Introduction Smart Healthcare is one of the most promising applications of 5G technology. Healthcare systems require reliable and ultra-low latency communication for real-time patient monitoring, emergency response, remote diagnostics, and telemedicine. 5G enables these capabilities through: \u25cf URLLC (Ultra-Reliable Low Latency Communication) \u25cf Network Slicing \u25cf Mobile Edge Computing (MEC) \u25cf High Reliability and Availability In this experiment, an end-to-end healthcare monitoring scenario was implemented using Open5GS and UERANSIM. A dedicated URLLC network slice was used to prioritize healthcare traffic, while MEC reduced communication delays by processing data closer to the user. 2. Objective The objectives of this experiment were: \u25cf Deploy an end-to-end 5G healthcare architecture. \u25cf Configure a dedicated URLLC network slice. \u25cf Establish communication between UE and edge server. \u25cf Demonstrate low-latency healthcare data transmission. \u25cf Validate the effectiveness of MEC and Network Slicing. 3. System Architecture The implemented architecture consisted of the following components: Component Function Open5GS Core 5G Core Network Functions UERANSIM gNB Simulated Radio Access Network UERANSIM UE Simulated Healthcare Device MEC Edge Server Local Data Processing Network Slice (SST 2) URLLC Healthcare Traffic Architecture Flow Healthcare UE \u2502 \u25bc gNB \u2502 \u25bc Open5GS Core \u2502 \u25bc MEC Edge Server \u2502 \u25bc Healthcare Application The healthcare data generated by the UE is transmitted through the 5G network and processed by the edge server with minimal delay. 4. Scenario Description A healthcare monitoring device was simulated as a 5G UE. The device periodically sends patient-related information such as: \u25cf Heart Rate \u25cf Blood Pressure \u25cf Oxygen Saturation (SpO \u2082 ) \u25cf Body Temperature The traffic is routed through a dedicated URLLC slice and processed by an edge server for real-time analysis. 5. Network Slice Configuration The UE was configured to use the URLLC slice. Slice Information Parameter Value Slice Type URLLC SST 2 Purpose Healthcare Monitoring UE Configuration sessions: - type: IPv4 apn: internet slice: sst: 2 This ensured that healthcare traffic utilized the dedicated low-latency slice. 6. Mobile Edge Computing Setup A local MEC server was deployed using a lightweight HTTP server. Edge Server Command python3 -m http.server 8080 The edge server processed healthcare data locally, avoiding delays associated with remote cloud communication. 7. Execution Procedure Step 1: Start Open5GS Core Verify that all Open5GS services are operational. Step 2: Start gNB Launch the UERANSIM gNB and establish NG Setup with the AMF. Step 3: Start UE Launch the UE configured with SST 2 (URLLC). Step 4: Verify Registration Ensure that: \u25cf UE registration is successful. \u25cf PDU session is established. \u25cf IP address is assigned. Step 5: Start MEC Server Run the local edge server: python3 -m http.server 8080 Step 6: Perform Latency Analysis Compare latency between: \u25cf Edge Server (Local MEC) \u25cf Remote Cloud Server 8. Results Healthcare Network Status Parameter Result Open5GS Core Operational gNB Connected Successful UE Registered Successful PDU Session Established Successful SST 2 Slice Selected Successful MEC Server Running Successful Latency Comparison Service Location Average Latency MEC Edge Server ~0.03 ms Remote Cloud Server ~120 ms 9. Performance Analysis Edge-Based Healthcare Communication Metric Value Network Slice SST 2 (URLLC) Processing Location Edge Average Latency ~0.03 ms Reliability High Observation The use of MEC significantly reduced communication delay, making the system suitable for real-time healthcare monitoring. Cloud-Based Communication Metric Value Processing Location Cloud Average Latency ~120 ms Observation Cloud processing introduced significantly higher latency due to additional network traversal and processing delays. 10. Benefits for Smart Healthcare The implemented architecture provides: \u25cf Real-Time Patient Monitoring \u25cf Faster Emergency Alerts \u25cf Reduced Communication Delay \u25cf Reliable Healthcare Data Transmission \u25cf Efficient Network Resource Utilization \u25cf Priority Handling through URLLC Slice Potential applications include: \u25cf Remote Patient Monitoring \u25cf Telemedicine \u25cf Smart Ambulance Systems \u25cf Wearable Health Devices \u25cf Remote Surgery Assistance 11. Figure Figure 9: End-to-End Smart Healthcare Demonstration The figure illustrates the complete communication path from the healthcare UE through the gNB and Open5GS Core to the MEC Edge Server using the URLLC network slice (SST 2). The architecture demonstrates how 5G Network Slicing and Mobile Edge Computing enable low-latency healthcare communication. 12. Key Observations \u25cf Open5GS successfully provided the 5G Core Network infrastructure. \u25cf UERANSIM simulated both the gNB and healthcare UE. \u25cf The UE successfully registered using the URLLC slice (SST 2). \u25cf Network slicing enabled dedicated healthcare traffic handling. \u25cf MEC significantly reduced communication latency. \u25cf Edge processing achieved approximately 0.03 ms latency. \u25cf Cloud-based communication exhibited approximately 120 ms latency. \u25cf The architecture effectively supported real-time healthcare applications. 13. Conclusion This experiment successfully demonstrated an end-to-end Smart Healthcare use case using Open5GS, UERANSIM, Network Slicing, and Mobile Edge Computing. The healthcare UE was configured to use a dedicated URLLC slice (SST 2) , ensuring priority handling of healthcare traffic. By processing data at the MEC server, communication latency was reduced to approximately 0.03 ms , compared to 120 ms for cloud-based communication. The results confirm that the combination of 5G Network Slicing and MEC provides the low-latency, high-reliability environment required for next-generation smart healthcare applications.",
